column1: Who will win the 2022 presidential election in Brazil?
column5: ['Jair Bolsonaro', 'João Doria', 'Ciro Gomes', 'Sérgio Moro', 'Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva', 'Another candidate']
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit', 'Elections and Referenda', 'Non-US Politics']
Many polls, including the Economist and El Pais, has Lula over 10 points higher than Bolsonaro.
This is weirdly close, some polls do show Bolsonaro winning, and any poll error is likely to favor him. Plus he is certain to cast doubt on the results if he loses.
I’m not at all as certain on this as we head into the final vote. Poll margin of error and the number of potential voters to be taken after the first round makes me cautious.

Lula is clearly favored by the polls but any systemic bias in the polls like we saw in the first round could make this very very close. I have little doubt that Bolsonaro will attempt a coup if he loses, but the electoral court is controlled by leftists who will likely certify the results anyway

All polling aggregatorshttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_2022_Brazilian_presidential_election#Bolsonaro_vs._Lulasee Lula ahead, however this may be biased similar to Clinton-Trump 2016 in US; Bolsonaro also outperformed his polls in the first round. However, predicting a runoff with the first round as a recall question is easier for pollsters and should lead only to small margins. So I am going higher for Lula again.Remains the uncertainty if, after a close defeat, Bolsonaro is pulling a Trump and won’t accept it.

After being cleared of corruption charges Lula da Silva seems to be the clear favorite and the only other competitor, Bolsonaro, has been trending down in the polls. I still think he has a chance but it has grown quite small in recent days.
The Economist Poll of Polls, as of Oct 26 - https://www.economist.com/interactive/brazil-2022 :
I decided to update this prediction and increase the percentage for Jair Bolonsaro. I think he has a better chance of winning than I originally thought, but still not enough to win the election.

Bolsonaro did better than the first round polls and if this error is repeated in the polls for the second round, may be that he actually has a much better chance than anticipated. Also Lula has been trending slight down since the first round https://www.economist.com/interactive/brazil-2022. Only one poll out of 10 puts them really close, with the rest leaving a healthy margin, but the error bars may still be quite wide on these polls. I am adjusting with much higher chance for a Bolsonaro win but still with a comfortable favor to Lula.

When looking on the internet, I found that Jair Bolsonaro and Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva are the top two contenders. I also looked at other predictions and found that these two are the most popular. On this website, https://www.as-coa.org/articles/poll-tracker-brazils-2022-presidential-election, I found that Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva is slightly ranked above Jair Bolsonaro. However, it seems that the gap is closing. I think that Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva still has a better chance of winning, but I will continue to update this prediction.
Fundamentals still favour Lula IMO, Bolsanoro will need both major switch from Lula voters first round and a majority of minority candidates.

Too close to call right now, and given pro Bolsonaro voters are hesitant to answer pollsters it’s my view Lula’s lead evaporates. See latest datafolha margins of error and 6% of voters undecided…this suggests Bolsonaro may also move ahead as they “reveal” themselves closer to the election.
I used the first round of voting outcome
L.ula does not have a son who is running the Bannon-Trump playbook where Bolsonaro does and it is starting to show.

According to a poll tracker on AS/COA, there is a close race between Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva and Jair Bolsonaro. The race was not close until recently in late 2022 and now the polls are showing a tight race between the two, with Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva in the lead against Jair Bolsonaro. Also, Lula has the approval of women and more economically challenged Brazilians. Although, Bolsonaro’s administration made some improvements to the Brazilian economy making it so that the majority of his voters say that there was an improvement in the economy which is different from only 13% of Lula’s voters stating this. Also after the presidential race, we see that Lula has 48.43% of the votes and Bolsonaro has 43.2%, putting Lula in the lead.

I put Lula at 51% because he has the approval of women and poor Brazilians. And Jair Bolsonaro at 49%, because Bolsonaro’s administration made some improvement to the Brazilian economy and has the support of Brazil’s business sector (https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20220923-brazil-s-business-sector-still-supports-bolsonaro-but-with-reservations
I predict that Lula will win with a 90% chance. The polls seem to be in Lula's favor significantly. As of the second round of the election, Lula holds about a 5% lead.
https://twitter.com/PesqBR2022/status/1581665449217265667
As in Italy, UK, India, Russia, and China, leadership errs on the side of far right. Polls show Lula's popularity following this trend.
Polls narrowing a lot more than I expected
most polls show Lula with a comfortable lead
I am surprised by how much support has gone to Bolsonaro. I still think that Lula will win, but I am not confident.

In spite of being second place at 1st round, incumbent president Bolsonaro's voters are more engaged, and more likely to convince the huge base of non voters or blank/null voters at 1st round to change and support Bolsonaro at the 2nd round. I acknowledge, however, the uncertainty is great for this election.
The first round confirmed the good lead for lulla and the polls also improved
Reasoning

Lula was less than 2% away from winning it all in the first round, he was surging late in the race, and I believe that the voters for the other candidates are more likely to vote for Lula than the incumbent Bolsonaro. All the same, I am wary of the possibility of conservative populist candidates over performing, as Bolsonaro has already proved he can, and there is the chance that he could cheat.

Outperformed in R1, but how is there a path for Bolsanaro? Lula was 1.6% off, Bolsanaro needs to take alot of Lula votes and win a big majority of minority candidates vote (who have come out for Lula and are mainly Anti-Bolsanaro).

A few decades ago, the Louisiana governor runoff involved Edwin Edwards, who had been a corrupt but not ineffective governor, and David Duke, who had been a nasty high-ranking official in the Klan. A bumper sticker emerged that said, "Vote for the crook. It's important." Brazil could use that about now. Stay tuned.
Polling has already taken place, with only runoff elections occurring if necessary.

Still belive it will be close. Bolsonaro had a Trump-effect in the first round. Strong performance from the right wing in the first vote. Much stronger than forecasted by the pros. Bolsonaros core demographic voters are likely to vote in the secound round too.

Bolsonaro has been a polarizing figure both within and outside of Brazil. Silva has already had great success in previous runs as he was already president of Brazil at one point, and is now running for his third term. With his cultivated personality of fairness and ambition, it is likely that Silva will be a breath of fresh air for many Brazilians, especially given Bolsonaro's infamously poor record around civil rights and medical care around other issues. Bolsonaro's motivated base will most likely not be enough to achieve victory this time.

Should Lula win, thanks to votes from the impoverished north, it will be tough to govern since several members of his government have won seats in the lower house, and the senate, where Workers Party has done poorly. Bolsonaro was the vote count winner in Sao Paulo state, and Rio de Janeiro state.

To me it is very clear that Lula will win the election. Whether it'll be 1st or 2nd round is the real question at this point - and I think even Bolsonaro's campaign recognizes that, in that they're trying to prevent a 1st round decision to draw out the elections.
Still belive it will be very, very close. Bolsonaro could have a Trump-effect. His core demographic voters are unlikely to participate in test polls.
For this weeks forecast, I predict that former president Luiz Inácio da Silva "Lula" (2003-2010) will win Brazil's 2022 presidential election.
Lula gaind in the last datapoll. But Bolsonaro is still in the game. His disprovement rate drops due to latest actions agianst inflation.
The polls show a narrowing difference between the top two candidates so i am adjusting the forecast.
Based on polls. The gap between Lula and Bolsonaro is closing, but Lula is still in the lead.
Bolsonaro went up a bit in the polls. https://www.as-coa.org/articles/poll-tracker-brazils-2022-presidential-election

Adjusting as Sergio Moro has dropped out.
While there is an overwhelming possibility that Lula will win this election, maybe in round 1, there are a few scenarios to consider.

Polls in Brasil press changing rapidly. Personality of Lula is becoming more attractive mensch than opponent who goes barefoot eats greasy fried meat and licks his fingers for the cameramen and camera women at a white hillbilly restaurant near Xollywood.

For those who follow the media and social-rad media sites in Brazil, it seems that Lula has been gone from drinking Kool-Aid to psychedelic Lulaid. Not only does his campaign (and Workers Party leader Gleisi Hoffmann offering vapid statements) lack momentum and effective leadership, but Lula has said that it is time for the 5 major economies of South America (U pick em) begin studying how to create their own currency, and call it the SUL, or SUR, or SOUTH (in spite of the fact that some still regard Mexico as part of "North America.)" And this in spite of China still being Brazil's top trade partner. Supposedly the economic guru that advises Lula claims the SUR-SUL will even out the living standards of the "major economies." One wonders whether it will instead help erode the aspirations of the young Brazilians who are working class levels 3-4 and seek to become part of an already eroding middle class ranges.

Brazil politics is very dynamic, I'd expect to change my mind very soon as the election campaigns start. Nevertheless, Lula's acquittal of crimes and Bolsonaro's erosion of base support seems to point to the public who seek a "return to the good 'ol days"...at least for now.
Rough guess based on a national survey.

According to several polls, Lula is leading compared to Bolsonaro (https://www.cnnbrasil.com.br/politica/datafolha-lula-tem-48-das-intencoes-de-votos-bolsonaro-22-e-moro-9/), some even say he might win in the first round. However, polls might be wrong and there are still 10 months to the elections.
Go (largely) with the flow.

Polls until early February 2022 have shown a stabilisation of the presidential election. No new strong candidates should show up by now. If Lula consolidates the left vote, he can even win in the first round with more than 50% national vote. If Lula goes to second turn with Bolsonaro his winning chances are strong also in the South and Southeast where PT struggled in last election. However, if Lula goes against Moro in second turn, Moro's rejection is lower than Bolsonaro for now, and this could make him more competitive against Lula. Even so, Lula is prone to win against Moro, especially if he consolidates also the centre vote, with party alliancs, and the indication of a centre VP as it seems to be his plan for now. Neither Ciro or Dória are well positioned to break the 5-10% margin
Former president and US friend Fernado Henrique Cardoso today endorsed Joao (the Brazillian Berlusconi) Doria for president.

If you check out open sources discussing Latin America you will note Biden's has named to the post of US Ambassador to Brazil Elizabeth Frawley Bagley. Here is a link to her Wikipedia bio. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth_Frawley_Bagley She is an old Latin American hand who has also served as US Ambassador to Portugal, Brazil's "mother country. And is a prominent Democratic Party fundraiser, supports womens and charitable causes and could be considered a powerful socialite, along the lines of what Claire Booth Luce was.

It feels the forecast should be an extreme version of the polls: - A 1% overall lead means a very slightly more than 50% chance of winning for that candidate (unless the field is very grouped or the polls generally extremely volatile); - but each extra %age point extra of lead is worth more than 1%age point extra of likelihood of winning. So if one candidate has a 20 point lead it sounds as if quite a bold prediction could be in order.

However, unless the margins in the polls are pretty close, they're probably right more often than wrong. There is at least some chance that Bolsonaro will actually win. There is also a non-zero chance that daSilva will meet with accidental death before the election. The nominees are stabbing himself fifteen or twenty times or pumping 20 or 30 rounds from an AK-47 onto his own back. Bolsonaro will declare it a suicide, and the Former Leader Of The Free World will congratulate him on his re-election. Still, the most likely is that daSilva will win and be allowed to live. Stay tuned.

With the highest rejection rates of any presumptive candidate (55%), Bolsonaro faces an uphill struggle to regain public support ahead of his expected re-election bid. In recent months he has embraced generous social programmes and reached out to the North-east region – a bastion of Lula support – but these moves do not yet appear to have translated into increased support

Bolsonaro (even though he is popular) his handling of the pandemic has caused many people to loose their lives as well as the economic impact on the country is taking its toll. Also, there is a lot of International pressure on Brazil because of the Amazon rainforest.
Incumbents usually win. And da Silva was just let out of jail. The only other option is F. Haddad. (22% chance)

Lula has led consistently in the polls since early 2021.

Politics, finance and sports fall in the same field of irrational behavior, the only difference is the currency used to measure each one. As of now, it seems that Brazilians are tired of Bolsonaro, and want LILS back, the question is will they hold their churrasco high enough.
Still 11 months to go and Lula is leading in the polls. Bolsonaro will fight to win with everything he's got and he may fight a negative result as well.
